Author: friends1980
Title: [ANN][ICO] Change - The First Decentralysed Crypto Bank [ICO September 16th]
Body: There is indeed finally official news. I am moderately optimistic.  The article is very clear and the final decision of the swap will remain subject to a community vote.  https://blog.getchange.com/change-token-swap-issuance-of-equity-like-tokens/  It seems the project took off on a bad start after having had some issues and discussions about the Bounty rewards. However, concerning the content and development of the project in itself, I'd dare to say the ride has been rather faultless.  FYI, the roadmap for the swap, followed by the community vote. It seemed to me some of these dates are important enough to copy them here:  Quote Important details:  14 Apr 2019 Release of token swap terms and CNG characteristics  1 Jul 2019 Release of updated token swap web page and FAQ  1 Sept 2019 Enable sending CAG to Change mobile application  16 Sept – 15 Dec 2019 Community voting and swapping period on a 1:1 ratio  16 Dec 2019 Announcement of the community vote results  20 Dec 2019 Latest delivery day of the first CNG tokens, if voting was favorable  1 Jan 2020 CNG trading on Change mobile application  1 Jan – 31 Dec 2020 Swapping period on a decreasing ratio  31 Dec 2020 Latest possible expiration date and equity conversion    If 51% vote in favor:  20 Dec 2019 Latest delivery day of the first CNG token  1 Jan 2020 CNG trading on Change mobile application  1 Jan – 31 Dec 2020 Swapping period on a decreasing ratio    If 51% vote against:  20 Dec 2019 All CAG will be returned to the original wallets

Author: semsyor
Title: [ANN][ICO] Change - The First Decentralysed Crypto Bank [ICO September 16th]
Body: Partnerships update: progress on integration and state of current partnerships  Progress on integration Past few days have been spent finalizing compliance and approvals for card process and IBAN integration (Integrator #1), meaning that as of this week if all goes according to plan most of the admin and compliance checks should have been completed. We will still need to work together with the integrator on coordinating how processor fees will be structured — however this should be a more dynamic process.  We started off working with 4 options — one (integrator #4) which fell of at the start due to lower appetite in terms of risk exposure and another one (integrator#3) was somewhat left in limbo while their compliance was designing new guidelines for working with companies in our sector. This later option has finalized its process and it looks like it will be hard to move ahead with them — however it was the case that a majority of players in the market was working with them so we’re glad that we had contingencies and started with 4 options.  With options #3 and #4 out of the picture and #1 moving along nicely you are probably wondering what’s happening with #2 — on this side as you might remember last week we submitted some new and innovative schematics to credit card company which are still currently being reviewed — however early feedback is positive — last thing that needs to be done here is monetary related negotiations.  In the mean time, we have also spoken and assessed 3 other potential integrators, one of which we might bring in as a further contingency. We also had the chance to attend a hackathon at one of the major banks in Estonia and got some very interesting contacts.  State of Current Partnerships We have seen a couple of questions in the chat regarding to what is the current status of announced partnerships so we’re happy to address that. We have decided to move in the direction of partnering with companies such as Mothership, Kyber, ETHLend, Zilla as well as Smartly, Bitof Property and Indorse — because we saw synergies between our products, however, we are all at the start of the journey as as you have seen everyone is focusing on building their core products at their own pace. Right now the partnerships are at a starting stage where we focus information and knowledge sharing to better understand how everyone is navigating the space and building relationships.  The next step will take place once partner’s respective product has reached a degree of maturity so we can actually integrate and as you might have noticed there has been impressive progress so far — everyone is excelling in their particular expertise. You will notice that we have not been pushing too aggressively on adding new partners despite receiving constant contacts from other parties, this has been so we can keep focusing on our current commitments — deliver on these and then expand.  E-Residency Goals E-Residency can be considered one of the most impressive achievements in the context of digital identity and it is surely paving the way for other countries to take a global approach on the topic of doing business and enabling a generation of digital nomads. Since the inception of Change we have had close contact and have worked to support each others vision. We do plan on executing more aggressively with E-Residency in the future and this will be done in a much more formal and direct manner than it has been done up to now.  With Change scaling we do envision E-Residency allowing global residents to access a series of Change services that for whatever reason might be restricted to Europe, an example you might have seen and real problem can be the fact that some cards companies only allow card issuance to the residents of a particular country and you are restricted from ordering such country if you are let’s say from outside the EU.  https://medium.com/changefinance/partnerships-update-progress-on-integration-and-state-of-current-partnerships-494ee0afc6e9

Author: crevbi
Title: [ANN][ICO] Change - The First Decentralysed Crypto Bank [ICO September 16th]
Body: HR update: hiring, hiring, hiring!  We’ve been keeping very busy to find the new members to our great team. Currently, our main focus is growing our engineering power. A rather tough task, considering the expectations on the candidates are high.    Careful consideration Right now we are building the core team of our company and the people joining us in this stage will play an integral role in creating the company’s future. This is why we are taking our time to very carefully analyze all applicants and although we have a lot of applications coming in, very few have passed the evaluation process.  Just like Sam Altman, the founder of Y combinator, brilliantly said:  “What we have seen is the best startups hire the least and the slowest in the very beginning. AirBnb took 9 months to hire their first person. Dropbox took “a long time” to hire their first person. Stripe took 6 months to hire their first person”  Evaluation process To be sure that anyone joining us is a perfect fit to the company culture and values, our hiring process consists of 4 steps:  1Pre-screening interview — 30–45 min call regarding applicant’s motivation, product thinking, main achievements, ambitions etc.  2Development team interview — 1.5h conference call focusing on technological knowledge and skill set, also conducting a small coding task.  3Product Manager interview — deeper look into the mindset to understand the candidate’s way of thinking and find out if there’s the “Special habanero sauce” in the inside we are looking for.  4CEO interview — final round to see the overall match to the company.  This week we had 15 pre-screening interviews, 4 tech team interviews, 4 product/design team interviews, and 2 meetings with our CEO Kristjan. We’re very happy to see that all the hard work we’ve put into interviewing has lead to the first results as well- we made 2 offers to promising candidates in the last few days.  https://medium.com/changefinance/hr-update-hiring-hiring-hiring-48d31e9e5df0

Author: YGung
Title: [ANN][ICO] Change - The First Decentralysed Crypto Bank [ICO September 16th]
Body: I've heard rumblings of disappointment with the bounty program and I'll dig deeper into the bounty program.  No disrespect, but I see people complaining about getting slighted fairly often in bounties and while I sympathize with those if it's due, I'm personally not at a point where I care to play judge and jury with any bounty program.  I'm PRETTY SURE there were people complaining about getting slighted in the SONM thread waaay back when about their bounty program, so there's that.  Do you know how many coins I would be into if I listened only to all the bad I hear about coins?  Even the big coins like Stellar and Ripple have controversial backstories, Check Qtum and Bitbay.  I'm not condoning it and I'm not trying derail this thread, but if it's not one thing it's something else.  That said I'm not going anywhere on this coin.  The whole crypto world is speculative, you taking risks no matter how you chop it up.  I'm not an all in investor; I have spread my risk out significantly.  I didn't come into crypto with my last or my life savings, I came in to crypto knowing full and well I could lose whatever I brought to the game.  I have a venture capitalist approach and I already conceded that somethings will lose.  I've accepted the risks and I live with it.  If you check my post history you won't ever see me whining or complaining about any crypto, and if I ever said something negative about a crypto when it was down it was jokingly (and I'm sure I owned it).

Every single member of the Change team has been ignoring me ever since I sent them emails/telegrams/... containing more than enough proof of how I barely got 1/5th of what I deserved. That to me is a big red flag.  If you check my post history, you won't find any whining in there, but we are all investors, which means we deserve to have a voice, even if our words aren't always positive. One last thing, if the change team had addressed my claims and explained to me why my calculations are wrong or why they can't pay me (and hundreds of others) the full rewards, I'd be 100% OK with it. The fact that they don't explain themselves, AND that they've been banning people left and right from their communication channels shows they're not as respectful, professional and reasonable as they want people to think.

Author: MiBambino
Title: [ANN][ICO] Change - The First Decentralysed Crypto Bank [ICO September 16th]
Body: In one sentence, people found out the Change team was funneling coins from the bounty budget into different addresses. In total I believe a couple hundred thousand coins got stashed away that should've gone to the bounty participants. When people started spreading this info, the team started banning them from their channels. I tried contacting them, showing them more than enough proof, as well as defending someone who hadn't even received a single dime, resulting in my own ban. The reason why i'm still searching for some justice is because blockchain was created to prevent stuff like this, yet the solution to corruption has become a weapon on its own. Either way i'm not expecting to get paid or receive apologies, I've since moved on and made good money on other projects. My main goal in the matter now is to warn people to be careful, that's all.  I also remember you, I believe I've silently agreed with you numerous times before haha; each time I see someone make sense on this forum (doesn't happen too often lol) I try to remember their names in case I ever see them posting about projects I don't know about. I don't pay attention to random fools talking about 'To the moon boiiii' without any backing or arguments, but reasonable, educated people like you are always worth listening to.

Author: gusgusest
Title: [ANN][ICO] Change - The First Decentralysed Crypto Bank [ICO September 16th]
Body: Hey everyone,  We just went through all of the feedback we’ve received through the Telegram channel and people PMing the team privately.  We put down every single proposal and filtered out the most popular items. Since currently the heavier focus is on payment card integration, we will probably not be able to address all of the issues for the public beta release, but we’ll try to tackle as many as possible.  Items high in the priority list: - adding present and historic values to transaction details - improving LTC wallet view - adding more contrast to the overview screen big C with regards to differentiating between different assets  We will be adding a considerable number of testers this week and hopefully we’ll receive more feedback both from new and already existing users.  Thanks!

Author: MiBambino
Title: [ANN][ICO] Change - The First Decentralysed Crypto Bank [ICO September 16th]
Body: I don't think thats the case. Like I said, I think the team is inexperienced, plus there might be more to it than meets the eye. I've been involved with a number of startups, and the budget you work with is usually very tight. It's not like they have one pot of 79 million coins, but rather a large number of addresses, all with various amounts of coins in them. Some budget goes to legal fees and such, some goes to marketing, .... I assume they underestimated the bounty amount and overestimated the ICO amount, which led to coins being used to pay marketeers/advisors/legal fees/development/... when in fact they were destined to be used as bounty rewards. That's why I believe we're seeing so much action in the addresses, because they're now looking into cutting certain budgets to make room for more bounty payments. Don't forget either that this situation wasn't planned. They expected to be done with bounties by the beginning of november. This means some people (krayola, jack, ...) now have to split their time between their planned tasks, and bounty handling. To conclude, I think there's more going on behind the scenes than meets the eye. For the record, I've been paid around 20% of what I believe I should get, but I'm waiting patiently. Soon, the large bulk of participants will be satisfied with the outcome, so if I haven't gotten my full rewards, I'll contact them then. Disclaimer: I'm in no way affeliated with Change, but I know how startups operate and what unexpected difficulties they can face.

Author: gusgusest
Title: [ANN][ICO] Change - The First Decentralysed Crypto Bank [ICO September 16th]
Body: A message from the team:  ---  Dear friends, this is a follow up to our previous message. Please read the following note carefully.  There was an unfortunate situation of miscommunication between the marketing team and our team responsible for the calculation and distribution of all affiliate and bounty rewards.  The rewards are still being distributed, and we look forward to send out all rewards in the next couple of weeks. If you haven't yet received your reward, please bear with us. We do value your participation and commitment to spreading the word about Change.  The Change team is committed to ensure that all rewards are calculated and distributed in the most fair way possible, and we apologise that this process is taking longer than expected. We have received some feedback that a portion of the rewards was yet to be distributed and we will look into each message individually before this matter is settled.  In case you have any questions, complaints, or suggestions regarding the reward programs, please fill in this form https://goo.gl/oedmwB    Thank you for your understanding.  ---

Author: YGung
Title: [ANN][ICO] Change - The First Decentralysed Crypto Bank [ICO September 16th]
Body: I think there's a misconception that virtually every ICO sells out but that's just not the case.  The ones that sell out may pump initially, but I think generally speaking, the large majority of ICOs that don't have a live product, mind blowing team/advisors, or powerful existing business partnerships will tank fairly fast after ICO.    Alot of it is product of exchanges too.  EtherDelta just isn't a well received exchange, and often times that's the first place for many of these coins.  Needless to say, its def a great time to accumulate.  Considering platform doesn't come til December, I wouldn't be surprised if it goes below 20 cents if another exchange isn't added between now and December.

Author: gusgusest
Title: [ANN][ICO] Change - The First Decentralysed Crypto Bank [ICO September 16th]
Body: Change doesn’t require a banking license to operate. This is because Change is essentially an app store of properly licensed fintech companies and it merely aggregates services offered by them to the customers.  In the longer run, as stated in the whitepaper, we are aiming for a banking license at a global financial hub, the selection of which will largely depend on the country we have most users from.

Author: silver12si
Title: [ANN][ICO] Change - The First Decentralysed Crypto Bank [ICO September 16th]
Body: OMG, The future of Change!  DESCRIPTION The Great Room presents OMG, The future of Change!  Date: 19 October 2017, Thursday Time: 6pm - 8pm Venue : The Great Room, 1 George Street #10-01 Singapore 049145 Price: $38 *Includes beer and snacks  Spend the night with OmiseGO & Change Bank  Featuring Vansa Chatikavanij, CEO at OmiseGO and Francisco Bernardo, CMO at Change Bank, moderated by Jeffrey Chua, Analyst at Golden Gate Ventures. We will be discussing the Ethereum projects that OmiseGO and Change Bank are working on, and its intended impact. Go to: https://www.sli.do/, enter event code: #ASK to send a question. Our guest speakers will do their best to answer all of them.  About OmiseGO: OmiseGO is building the OmiseGO network which is a public Ethereum-based financial technology for use in mainstream digital wallets, that enables real-time, peer-to-peer value exchange and payment services agnostically across jurisdictions and organizational silos, and across both fiat money and decentralized currencies.  About Charge Bank: Change is the financial institution of the future. On top of making cryptocurrencies spendable, Change bundles the best fintech companies in the world to create a sophisticated marketplace of financial services. --------  About the Speakers:  Vansa Chatikavanij, Managing Director at OmiseGO Vansa has led dynamic teams of engineers, economists and social scientists to deliver bottom line results in global organizations. In her former role at the World Bank Group, she led teams to roll- out international development programs worth over US $1 billion across finance inclusion, infrastructure investments, and environmental and social development areas. Her international experience extends South and East Asia emerging markets including Bangladesh, Cambodia, India, the Maldives, Lao PDR, Myanmar, Pakistan and Vietnam. Currently, Vansa serve as an advisor to Loxley Public Company Ltd., and Sky Visual Imaging Venture.  At OmiseGO, she is responsible for ensuring efficient project delivery, establishment and realization of the long-term business strategy, business development and partnerships.  Francisco Bernardo, CMO at Change Bank CMO at Change Bank, building the financial institution of the future. Management graduate from NUS and SMU, with previous startup and VC experience.  Our Moderator: Jeffrey Chua, Analyst at Golden Gate Ventures Jeffery graduated from Pace University with a Bachelors of the arts in Economics, IBF level 1 certified. He has been with the firm since 2015. Jeffery's core duties include Deal sourcing, fundraising, valuations, due diligence, M&A and portfolio management, and he covers Agritech, Edutech, Insurtech, Blockchain, and fintech companies.

Author: KingArbinV
Title: [ANN][ICO] Change - The First Decentralysed Crypto Bank [ICO September 16th]
Body: This article just compares team, fees and some other basic elements. Team actually is better in Change, then in other project , it is good moment. But financing finacial project, you need also to deep inside token model. And here Change sucks. You could simply find out actual 17x difference in expected returns between Polybius and Change in favour of first one. It seems Change team is too greedy!  As far as it concerns 'Polybius is scam' - but most of them is soft scam! For instance MonacoCard: they get on ICO near $25mlns, but it is already known that they launched crypto-card leveraging third-party WaveCrest solution. It costs them nearly $300/$400thnd. + 2mln for marketing, and rest of money was pocketed-out. So no doubt Change will obtain EMI licence and be able to launch product - they openly stated in wp that will use third-party solution for card-issuance, see page 25. The question is that $4/$5mln is enough even taking into account thier innovative API for other fintech, so asking investors for $50mln is soft scam too.

Title: [ANN][ICO] Change - The First Decentralysed Crypto Bank [ICO September 16th]

Author: KingArbinV
Title: [ANN][ICO] Change - The First Decentralysed Crypto Bank [ICO September 16th]
Body: Nothing new - this project is just second Estonian-grounded project simply extending ideas of previous Estonian digital Polybius bank, which first proposed idea of blending banking services with financial marketplace. The slight difference is that Polybius team was shy to mention cryptos in conjuction to banking services, but these guys dare to do it. As far as it concerns crypto accounts and crypto-nominated debit cards - there are hundreds of such start-ups and even well-established companies like MonacoCard, Coinsbank, UQUID etc.  Economic model is also weak - in WP they promise to distribute only 10% of annual income to tokens holders and try to sell only 40% of token supply for near 50mln. For instance, Polybius bank engaged to distribute 20% of annual income for all tokens, from which 93% are sold to public. Thus from financial perspective Polybius token is 17x more attractive then CAG.  Given these considerations I restrain to participate in this ICO and not recommend anybody to engage in it.

Title: [ANN][ICO] Change - The First Decentralysed Crypto Bank [ICO September 16th]
Body: Hey,  I am wondering if you've read the whitepaper. Please do.  In addition to a crypto card, Change is offering a financial services marketplace. The philosophy behind the Change model is the understanding that banks which focus on all key financial products at once don't really excel in any product and therefore offer mediocre services. We at Change believe that fintech companies specializing in one financial product offer a much better service than a traditional bank.  By aggregating a variety of fintech companies together into one marketplace, a customer of Change gets to cherry pick the best loan offerings, ETF investments, real-estate investments and insurance options the market has to offer. A banking experience from one app with the market’s best financial services.

Author: gusgusest
Title: [ANN][ICO] Change - The First Decentralysed Crypto Bank [ICO September 16th]
Body: Change’s competitors more or less represent traditional banks - one centralized platform where the operator offers a range of financial services. Change is essentially the contrary to it.   The philosophy behind the Change model is the understanding that banks which focus on all key financial products at once don't really excel in any product and therefore offer mediocre services. We at Change believe that fintech companies specializing in one financial product offer a much better service than a traditional bank.   By aggregating a variety of fintech companies together into one marketplace, a customer of Change gets to cherry pick the best loan offerings, ETF investments, real-estate investments and insurance options the market has to offer. A complete banking experience from one app with the market’s best financial services.

Author: gusgusest
Title: [ANN][ICO] Change - The First Decentralysed Crypto Bank [ICO September 16th]
Body: People apply for e-Residency for various reasons. Some live in Estonia and want to conveniently access public sector services, others want to set up a company to do business within the European Union, others want to very securely sign documents in the European Union. Or as the e-Residency team puts it:  "For example, e-Residency would allow an Indian entrepreneur to establish an Estonian company that he runs from Singapore to serve clients based in Germany. He'd also be able to use his digital signature to sign contracts with customers throughout the European Union. All of it would be done online, remotely, and completely hassle-free."  So in short, for e-Residents, Change will be an additional opportunity/functionality/comfort e-Residency brings them.

Author: MalReynolds
Title: [ANN][ICO] Change - The First Decentralysed Crypto Bank [ICO September 16th]
Body: Pre-sale data:  https://etherscan.io/address/0x78E0743B2cC9967BaC4643D559A027FA53F6BC88  Only about 58% of available pre-sale tokens sold to around 700 people / accounts.  Of the tokens sold, 40% went to 4 people / accounts.  Around $8M of funding raised in presale, less than $5M from the "crypto community at large".  Not sure I would use the word "very".  The word "bank" is being thrown around without a banking license, their Mastercard provider is balking at diving into cryptocurrencies with them, and e-resident / Estonia has no tangible connection to this project that I can see.  I was interested, and their whitepaper graphics sure are slick, but ultimately I didn't invest.

Author: gusgusest
Title: [ANN][ICO] Change - The First Decentralysed Crypto Bank [ICO September 16th]
Body: Thanks for taking a look and providing feedback. Getting back to a few of the points.  Regarding card agreements:  Change started off as a fiat mobile banking application with a beta app and a Mastercard agreement. As Change pivoted to cryptocurrencies, we are currently working on modifications to the platform and renegotiating the Mastercard agreement to make the platform and card payments cryptocurrency compatible. We are also working with multiple issuers to ensure the seamless rollout of cards.  Regarding e-Residency:  Regarding the e-Residency project and tangible connection. Both Kaspar Korjus (Head of e-Residency), and Ott Vatter (Head of Global Growth) are openly supporting the project. Check out this recent tweet from the Head of e-Residency:  https://twitter.com/kasparkorjus/status/906142395221278725  There are also a variety of articles available, check out this one:  http://www.marketwatch.com/story/change---the-first-decentralised-crypto-bank-for-e-residents-2017-09-04

Author: MalReynolds
Title: [ANN][ICO] Change - The First Decentralysed Crypto Bank [ICO September 16th]
Body: I understand that e-Residency personnel are on your side and are promoting your project.  But the article says, "In order for the marketplace to be regulatorily compliant, Change is building a multi-tiered standardized KYC (Know-Your-Customer) utility."  This sentence implies that just being an "e-Resident" isn't enough for Change Bank KYC, that there will be other "tiers" of ID created by Change Bank outside of the e-Resident program.    So...will registering in Estonia's e-Resident program with its 100-Euro fee be required to obtain access to Change Bank services?   Yes or No?  If the answer is no, then what is the point or advantage of having e-Residency here?

Author: gusgusest
Title: [ANN][ICO] Change - The First Decentralysed Crypto Bank [ICO September 16th]
Body: Hey,  Being an e-Resident means you have performed the most thorough KYC possible (last tier), which means you most probably do not have to perform additional KYC. So anyone who is an e-Resident gets easy access to investment services on the platform. People who aren't e-Residents have to carry out extensive KYC on the Change platform, so setting up an account just takes more time and customers need to send document copies. There are currently more than 22 000 e-Residents for whom the account setup is seamless and fast.

Author: MalReynolds
Title: [ANN][ICO] Change - The First Decentralysed Crypto Bank [ICO September 16th]
Body: So I think you have answered "no" to my original question.  Apparently Change Bank users can get access to your services without paying the 100-euro fee to become an Estonia e-Resident.   The 22,000 e-Residents have Change Bank setup that is seemless, fast and costly.  Sounds to me like "easy access to Change Bank" is being used to help justify 100 Euro payments made by prior e-Resident signups, and Estonian e-Residence offers no real advantages worth a 100-euro fee to new Change Bank signups.

Author: biggydeen
Title: [ANN][ICO] Change - The First Decentralysed Crypto Bank [ICO September 16th]
Body: Why is de cap based on ETH? That makes zero sense. The price of Ethereum dropped $100 in just a few days. In just one month the price even dropped from almost $400 to $150. How can you even fund a project based on cryptocurrencies when they are so volatile?  It seems to me that raising funds this way is based on nothing. If the hard cap is 200.000 ETH you can potentially raise $76 million when the Ethereum price hits $380 or $40 million when the ETH price hits $200. You have no clue in advance what the price of ETH will be at the time of the ICO.  So how can a hard cap of 200.000 ETH be justified? The hard cap should be based on actual dollars needed and then recalculated to the amount of ETH needed.  Besides, how does the public know how much money will be raised? How much of those 200.000 ETH will be sold for dollars right away? I doubt every single ETH will be sold right away.  Also, the white paper only uses percentiles. For example, 25% of the funds go to licensing and partnerships. And how much is 25% of the funds exactly? No one knows. This is based on the price of ETH which may drop or rise significantly in a matter of days.  Don't get me wrong, its sounds like a great project but funding ICO's based on cryptocurrencies makes no sense at all. I see this happen with a lot of ICO's.  Millions of dollars are raised but no one knows how much. And if all these millions are actually needed. The white paper only talks about ETH. That makes zero sense.  What will happen in the following scenarios:  - Hard cap is 200.000 ETH.  Scenario 1: price of ETH falls to $250 on the day of the ICO: $50 million is raised Scenario 2: price of ETH raised to $400 on the day of ICO: $80 million is raised Scenario 3: On the day of ICO the price is $400 but drops to $280 a month later: how much money is raised?  On a side note, these amounts are only raised if all ETH received in the ICO are directly converted to dollars. Which I doubt will happen.  Putting a hard cap based on cryptocurrency basically means there is no hard cap. Because you might raise $50 million, $20 million, $100 million, etc.  The only right way of funding an ICO is based on the amount of money you need. If you need $50 million then the hard cap should be $50 million. Then the amount of ETH needed should be based on the amount of $50 million. Meaning the hard cap based on ETH will change every day until the ICO takes place. And all raised ETH should be sold for dollars right away. But that does not make any sense at all either. Because if the market is dipping, it would not be wise to sell all ETH right away.  Maybe I'm missing something. But I have zero understanding how funding a project based on volatile cryptocurrencies can work.

Author: MiBambino
Title: [ANN][ICO] Change - The First Decentralysed Crypto Bank [ICO September 16th]
Body: The reason ETH is chosen is because it solves the problem of multiple currencies. I think investors all over the world are interested, so using ETH as a base currency makes it easier/safer/faster to contribute than using Bitcoin or our own federal currencies. Also, Eth has a lot of potential to grow right now, so they're probably fine with raising money this way. I'm sure they prepare for the worst (ETH drops back to 100$) and hope for the best (ETH shoots past 400$), so i'm guessing they need around 20 million to keep things rolling. Last, they add the hard cap to make their product more scarse, it's a well known marketing tool. Setting a cap of 20 million seems a lot less scarse than setting a cap of 200.000 ETH

Author: sbogovac
Title: [ANN][ICO] Change - The First Decentralysed Crypto Bank [ICO September 16th]
Body: Sorry, but "too little, too late".  I was genuinely interested and asked a simple question:  Quote from: sbogovac on September 01, 2017, 07:23:52 AM Quote from: xrpdavid on August 31, 2017, 07:55:56 PM Wist je dat je met de Change Card straks vanaf dag 1 kunt betalen op ALLE miljoenen plekken ter wereld waar MasterCard wordt geaccepteerd?  In welk opzicht is dat anders dan; Bitpay, Cryptopay, Xapo, Wirex, Shift, Bitstamp of "any other" Bitcoin debit card leverancier?  Dus vanwaar jouw conclusie dat:  Quote from: xrpdavid on August 31, 2017, 07:55:56 PM Dit [...] een grote ICO [gaat] worden [?!?]   Translation:  Quote from: sbogovac on September 01, 2017, 07:23:52 AM Quote from: xrpdavid on August 31, 2017, 07:55:56 PM Did you know that with the Change Card you can pay from day one on ALL the millions of places in the world where MasterCard is accepted?  In what way is that different from; Bitpay, Cryptopay, Xapo, Wirex, Shift, Bitstamp or any other Bitcoin debit card vendor?  So how do you concluded that:  Quote from: xrpdavid on August 31, 2017, 07:55:56 PM This [...] is [going to be] a big ICO [?!?]   And your initial reply is:  Quote from: xrpdavid on September 02, 2017, 11:26:18 AM [...] Heb je de whitepaper gelezen? [...]  Translation:  Quote from: xrpdavid on September 02, 2017, 11:26:18 AM [...] Did you read the whitepaper? [...]  Which is not an answer but a counter question and deflection. And then, after I decline to read anything because I "know enough" - to top it all off - I get a PM from you:  Quote from: xrpdavid on September 03, 2017, 07:37:59 AM wtf, hoi puber.. ik verwijs je niet naar een whitepaper.. ik vraag aan je of je de whitepaper hebt gelezen, omdat ik vermoed van niet.. ga even ergens anders gefrustreerd doen dan in mijn draadje svp    Translation:  Quote from: xrpdavid on September 03, 2017, 07:37:59 AM wtf, hi teen [literally: someone in puberty].. I did not refer you to a whitepaper .. I asked you whether you have read the whitepaper because I suspect you didn't .. Please go act frustrated somewhere else instead of my thread    Well, I'm done with Change if you don't mind.  Good luck to the Change team! You're going to need it; with people like xrpdavid representing you...

Author: dragosg
Title: [ANN][ICO] Change - The First Decentralysed Crypto Bank [ICO September 16th]
Body: sbogovac  - Apology for any issues you have experienced in the dutch thread - we are very happy to answer questions - with regards to threads in other languages - it is very difficult for us to keep track of them - as we dont speak those languages and they are usually set up as part of our bounty program.  As such quality control there is very hard thing. Never the less- no excuses - its out fault and for that please accept my apology.  One thing that we do very well is answer questions - the best forum for this is the telegram group where we have 1000+ people and we answer all questions in a public forum - nothing to hide. I would strongly encourage you to join us there.  With regards to your questions - the answer is quite simple - change is not much different than the other cards - however, the card and wallet are meant to serve as a gateway into the change market place - where we bring on board a series of established fintech partners into which you can deploy your capital.  Our main value prop is the marketplace and not the card.  Please let me know if that makes sense and do join us over on Telegram. you can find the link on our website.  Best Regards,  Dragos

Author: gusgusest
Title: [ANN][ICO] Change - The First Decentralysed Crypto Bank [ICO September 16th]
Body: The ICO is carried out by companies registered in Estonia (in the European Union), where cryptocurrencies are not regulated. The platform is designed to work as a global application, meaning it will not be tied to any particular country. As both the SEC (US) and the MAS (Singapore) have issued notices on ICOs, we have received council to not accept investors from respective countries.

Author: gusgusest
Title: [ANN][ICO] Change - The First Decentralysed Crypto Bank [ICO September 16th]
Body: Change started off as a fiat product with a closed beta (https://changeapp.wordpress.com/2017/05/26/we-have-invited-the-first-testers-to-our-office/) and a Mastecard agreement. We are currently working on modifciations to the product to make it cryptocurrency compatible.  Regarding the marketplace - we are currently integrating with the first three fintech companies (Smartly (https://www.smartly.sg), Danabijak (https://danabijak.com) and BitOfProperty (http://www.bitofproperty.com/).

Author: gusgusest
Title: [ANN][ICO] Change - The First Decentralysed Crypto Bank [ICO September 16th]
Body: Change doesn't intend to apply for a traditional banking licence at first, which is due to the decentralised marketplace model. However, in the future we do wish to offer our customers IBAN accounts etc. On the contrary, this requires vast amounts of capital reserves.  If you are more interested in banking licenses, I could possibly arrange a call with the team to walk through the financial plan. Please leave a private message so I could get you in touch with the team.

Author: dragosg
Title: [ANN][ICO] Change - The First Decentralysed Crypto Bank [ICO September 16th]
Body: Hi guys, thank you very much for your enthusiasm - change coin serves as a utility for accessing all these partners so far we have at least 3 partners ready to roll.  One thing I would like to highlight is that Chance is VC funded and has been operating for 2 years with its on development team.  The partners - Smartly - Danabijak and BitofProperty have been individually funded by Venture Capital and have been operating individually and independent as well. You can go to their website and use their products at the moment as they are live.  These partners are based out of Singapore, Estonia  and Indonesia where they have they own development teams.  You can think of Change as a marketplace that will allow you to access all these partners, as we will be onboarding partners with finished and functioning products globally - so far partners we are working with are in the insurance sector, peer to peer crypto lending as well as real estate in countries such as Japan, Australia, Estonia, UK , Thailand. We are working with them for on-boarding and setting up the infrastructure.  If you have any other suggestions for partners that provide financial services/ products we would be keen to look into it.  Hope that helps answer your questions.

Author: Hardforker78
Title: [ANN][ICO] Change - The First Decentralysed Crypto Bank [ICO September 16th]

Author: dragosg
Title: [ANN][ICO] Change - The First Decentralysed Crypto Bank [ICO September 16th]
Body: Thank you very much for your question.  Roger adds great amount of value not just as the EX-CEO of DHL - having ran the company out of Germany , Singapore and Miami. He also runs a successful fintech firm out of Singapore and manages a Private Equity firm that invests in Europe.  Our goal is to be a marketplace with global reach - Roger will be instrumental in helping us achieve this due to both his knowledge of running one of the most successful companies in the world but at the same time due to his strategic guidance and not to mention wide network.  We will be able to attract fintech partners from all over europe and asia as part of phase one due to Roger`s help.  He is of immense value and we very excited that out of all the fintech icos out there he is supporting us.  Hope that helps answer you question.

Title: [ANN][ICO] Change - The First Decentralysed Crypto Bank [ICO September 16th]

Author: spinachcoin
Title: [ANN][ICO] Change - The First Decentralysed Crypto Bank [ICO September 16th]
Body: Alright guys, as someone who has worked very closely with bankers and that overall environment let me explain something to you.  Banks SUCK ! not because they handle money but because people suck ! the motivation and incentive in a bank is to backstab and try to push yourself up the ladder -so you will have people across the the departments of bank constantly tripping each other up and making life difficult inside the bank for each other now this translates into high level of incompetency and inefficiency.  I personally welcome this project and these type of projects because they are not banks - yes they might serve the purpose but at their core they are tech firms and the think about tech firms is they have done a decent job at building strong healthy cultures.  In this market place scenario from what I can see - each company functions independently so there is no cross department BS and slog - giving everyone the chance to excel at what they do and serving the end user ie ME.  Now I put money in crypto all the time and make gains BUT if i want to take those gains and put them into something more stable its a nightmare ! especially in the country that I live in and especially because i tend to change countries every couple of years.  If this project will allow me to move my BTC into stocks, etfs property by a click or 2 instead of 2 months , then I am IN! if you know anything about the markets is that timing matters and if this removes the 7 days BS and allows me to buy into opportunities when they come up as opposed to 7 days after then Haleluja !

Author: gusgusest
Title: [ANN][ICO] Change - The First Decentralysed Crypto Bank [ICO September 16th]
Body: Just looked up Minerva. It looks to be a payment solution? I think Minerva and Change are quite different.  In addition to payments, Change is looking to offer a full suite of cryptocurrency-based financial services in a single app. One key value proposition of Change lies in accessing hundreds of specialized cutting-edge financial services, all from one place without having to sign up and perform KYC on every single platform.

Author: lesom
Title: [ANN][ICO] Change - The First Decentralysed Crypto Bank [ICO September 16th]
Body: The idea is good, but not new, it is indicated that this is The First Decentralysed Crypto Bank, but similar projects have already been, although not very successfully decorated, good luck to you

Author: dragosg
Title: [ANN][ICO] Change - The First Decentralysed Crypto Bank [ICO September 16th]
Body: Hi Lesom,  Thank you very much for your message and very good point, here is my answer:  There are other crypto banks yes ! however in terms of decentralisation we function more as a marketplace that will allow you to access other independent partners that supply different specialised financial services - while other crypto banks focus on building entire departments under one roof we are more of a gateway into different products.  The advantage here is every partner does their own thing and have their own expertise, Change curates the partners and makes sure you get access to them.  Please let me know if that makes sense.
